Members of the Welsh National Assembly, known today as AM (Assembly Members), are not entirely satisfied with the proposal that their title may be changed to MWP (Member of the Welsh Parliament).
The proposal comes as a result of plans to change the name of the National Assembly to the Welsh Parliament.
Representatives from across the political spectrum fear that this could lead to ridicule.
A Labour representative explained his group was concerned because "it rhymes with Twp and Pwp."
For readers outside of Wales: In Welsh, twp means "dusted", and pwp means "beautiful".
A representative for Wales party Plaid Cymru said the group as a whole was "dissatisfied" and that they have proposed alternatives.
A representative for the Welsh section of the Conservative Party said his group was "open" to the name change, but noted that the pronunciation of the MWP is very close to the word "Muppet", which, in addition to being the name of some well-known dolls, is also a British slang word for "dust".
In this context, the Welsh letter W is pronounced in a similar manner as the letter U is pronounced in the English Yorkshire dialect, more like an "uh" sound.
The Assembly Commission, which is currently developing laws to introduce the name change, said: “Of course, it is the members themselves who have the final right of designation in terms of which name they are to be referred to.”
The Government of Wales Act 2017 gave the Welsh National Assembly permission to change its own name.
In June, the Commission published the results of a public hearing that showed general support for renaming the National Assembly to the Welsh Parliament.
As for the title of the representatives, the Commission supported WMPs (Welsh Parliament Members), but the alternative MWP received the most support during the public hearing.
Representatives are reportedly proposing other options, but getting all parties to come to an agreement could lead to a headache for Parliament President Elin Jones, who is scheduled to deliver a legislative draft of the name change over the next couple of weeks.
The legislation around the reform will include other changes in how the National Assembly works, including rules for disqualification of representatives and the design of the committee system.
Representatives have the last right to vote on what to call them when they debate the legislation.
