John Edward: Language skills are crucial for world citizens
Scotland’s free schools continue to demonstrate academic excellence, and this has continued in 2018 with another one year of excellent exam results. These are supported by individual and joint success in sports, art, music and other social measures.
These schools, represented by The Scottish Council of Independent Schools, have more than 30,000 students across Scotland, and work hard to deliver the very best school experience to both students and parents.
Fris schools aim to prepare their students for further and higher education, their chosen careers and their position as world citizens.
As an educational institution that can design and implement a tailored school curriculum, we see that modern languages are still a popular and in demand elective discipline at schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you speak to a man in a language he understands, when words reach his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, his words reach his heart.”
This is a powerful reminder that we can’t just stick to English when we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
From this year’s exam results, we see that language is at the top of the table with the highest percentages of admissions from free schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who studied foreign languages received the grade A.
The data, obtained from the council’s 74 member schools, showed that 72 percent of students received the grade A in Mandarin, while 72 percent of those who studied German, 69 percent of those who studied French and 63 percent of those who studied Spanish also received A.
This illustrates that free schools in Scotland support foreign languages as a crucial skill children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Language as a choice of subjects is now valued at the same level as real sciences such as science, technology, engineering and mathematics on the curriculum for free schools and other places.
A survey conducted by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills in 2014 showed that, for reasons stated by employers to have problems occupying a vacant position, 17 percent could be attributed to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming increasingly important to prepare young people for a future career.
As more and more job opportunities require language skills, these skills become crucial in a globalized world.
If you have learned a second language, these lifelong skills will bring real benefits in the future, no matter what career you choose.
Being able to communicate directly with people from other countries will automatically give a multilingual person a competitive edge.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 British adults in 2013, 75 percent were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to have a conversation, and French was the only language a two-digit number of participants (15 percent) could speak.
This is why investing in language training is now crucial for today’s children.
Being able to speak more languages, especially those related to emerging economies, will give children better opportunities to find good jobs.
In Scotland, each school teaches in different languages.
Many schools will focus on the more classic modern languages, while others will teach languages that are considered to be most valuable to the UK on the road towards 2020, such as Mandarin and Japanese.
No matter what interests your child, there will always be a selection of languages to choose from at the nursery schools, with teachers who are experts in this field.
Scottish schools aim to create a learning environment that will prepare children and equip them with the knowledge and skills they need to succeed, no matter what the future brings.
It cannot be denied in today’s global business environment that language is still crucial to the country’s future, and this must be reflected in teaching.
Modern languages should actually be considered “international communication skills”.
Free schools will continue to offer this opportunity, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
We have to do it right.
John Edward is head of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (Scotland Free School Council)
