North Korea 'in no way' will agree to unilateral disarmament without confidence
North Korea’s foreign minister told the UN on Saturday that continued sanctions bolstered the distrust of the United States and that the country will in no way agree to unilaterally release its nuclear weapons under such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the World Organization’s annual general meeting that North Korea has implemented “significant goodwill measures” over the past year, such as halting nuclear and missile tests, dismantling the nuclear test area and promising not to spread nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
“We haven’t seen a similar response from the United States,” he said.
“Without confidence in the United States, we have no confidence in our national security, and under such circumstances we will not, under any circumstances, unilaterally disarm ourselves first.”
Ri repeated well-known North Korean complaints about Washington's resistance to a gradual nuclear disarmament, where North Korea is rewarded for gradual disarmament, but his statement was significant because it did not reject unilateral nuclear disarmament completely, as Pyongyang has done previously.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump in Singapore on June 12, at the very first meeting between a sitting president of the United States and a North Korean leader, where Kim promised to work against “nuclear disarmament of the Korean Peninsula,” while Trump guaranteed North Korea’s security.
North Korea has called for a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said Pyongyang must first release its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also opposed calls to reduce strict international sanctions against North Korea.
“The U.S. insists on ‘nuclear disarmament first’, lifting pressure through sanctions to achieve its goal by force, and even opposing ‘the declaration of the end of the war’,” Ri said.
“The belief that sanctions can force us to knee is a dream of desire for people who know nothing about us.
But the problem is that the continued sanctions create further mistrust.”
Ri did not mention plans for a second meeting between Kim and Trump that the US leader stressed in front of the UN earlier this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae over the past five months, adding: "If the other party in this disarmament case was South Korea, rather than the United States, the nuclear arms of the Korean Peninsula would not have been as locked as it is."
The tone of Ri’s speech, however, was very different from last year’s when he told the UN General Assembly that an attack on mainland America with North Korea’s missiles was inevitable after Trump called Kim a “missile man” on a suicide mission.
After threatening to “completely destroy” North Korea last year, Trump stood in front of the UN this year and praised Kim for being brave enough to take disarmament steps, but said much work remains to be done, and sanctions must remain in place until North Korea is nuclear-armed.
On Wednesday, Trump saw that he didn’t have a time frame for this, saying, “It doesn’t matter if it takes two years, three years or five months.”
