Students at Harvard take a course in getting enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year will help students get more sleep by tackling the growing ukulele culture by plunging through the night with coffee drinks as fuel.
One scholar found that students at the world’s best university often had no clue how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, prepared the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He started the course after he gave a lecture on the effect of lack of sleep on learning.
“After the lecture, a girl came over to me and said, ‘Why hasn’t anyone said this before?’
She said no one had ever told her how important sleep was, and that surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, which starts up this year, explains how important it is with good sleep habits to be able to perform academically and athletically, and for the general condition.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and the university’s health services professor, said the university decided to start the course after they saw that students suffered from severe sleep deprivation.
The course, which lasts for one hour, has a series of interactive tasks.
In one section there is a picture of a room in a dormitory where students can click on coffee cups, curtains, sneakers and books and learn about the effects of caffeine and light and how athletic performance is affected by lack of sleep, and how important it is with a sleep routine.
In another part, participants learn how prolonged sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A campus map with interactive icons makes participants think about their own daily routine.
“We are aware that this will not change the behavior of students immediately.
But we believe that they have the right to know about this, just as you have the right to know about the risk of smoking,” said Professor Czeisler.
There is still some pride in being able to snuggle all night, he said, adding that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students led to sleep deprivation being an increasing problem.
Good sleep should be a student’s “secret weapon” against stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said – even as a means of weight gain, as sleep deprivation puts the brain in starvation mode, leading to a constant sense of hunger.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old from California who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler prepare the course. He took one of the classes to the professor last year, his first year at Harvard.
He said that the course inspired him to work for a course that was available for the entire campus.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all master’s students to take a similar study program before enrolling in the university.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students set an alarm for when to lie down as well as for when to get up, and that they need to be aware of the harmful effects of blue light from electronic screens and LED lights. This type of light can disrupt the circadian rhythm and lead to sleep difficulties.
