Almanac: The Invention of the Geiger Teller
And now a page from the "Sunday Morning" almanac: September 30, 1882, 136 years ago, was the day when the future physicist Johannes Wilhelm "Hans" Geiger was born in Germany.
Geiger developed a method for detecting and measuring radioactivity, a discovery that led to the apparatus we know today as the Geiger teller.
The Geig teller has been an important part of science since then, and also became a part of popular culture through the 1950 film "Bells of Coronado", with scientists Roy Rogers and Dale Evans:
Man: "What in the world is it?"
