The technology legend’s latest project, Inrupt, is a company that builds on Berners-Lee’s open source platform Solid.
On Solid, users can choose where their data should be stored and which people have access to the information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee joked that the purpose is "world domination".
“We have to do it now,” he said of the start.
“This is a historic moment.”
The app uses Solid’s technology to allow people to create their own “personal data warehouse online” or a POD.
It may contain contact lists, work lists, calendars, music libraries, and other personal and professional tools.
It’s as if Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify are all available in one browser at a time.
What is unique about the personal data stored online is that it is entirely up to the user who should have access to that type of information.
The company calls it "personal authorization through data".
The idea behind Inrupt is, according to the company’s CEO, John Bruce, that the company should provide resources, process and relevant expertise to make Solid available to everyone.
The company currently consists of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, some hired developers on contract to work with the project and a bunch of volunteer programmers.
From this week, technology developers around the world can create their own decentralized apps using the tools available on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee said he and his team are not talking to “Facebook and Google about whether or not to introduce something completely new, which will make their business models completely revamped overnight.
“We don’t ask for your permission.”
In a post on Medium published on Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote that Inrupt’s “mission is to offer commercial energy and an ecosystem that helps protect the integrity and quality of the new network built on Solid.”
In 1994, Berners-Lee transformed the Internet when he established the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months, Berners-Lee has been an important voice in the debate on net neutrality.
Although he is launching Inrupt, Berners-Lee will still be the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Web Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
“I’m incredibly optimistic about the next era of the web,” Berners-Lee added.
Bernard Vann: Celebration of Victoria Cross Recipients of World War I
The only priest in the English Church who was awarded a Victoria Cross during World War I as a combatant was celebrated in his hometown after 100 years.
Lieutenant Colonel and priest Bernard Vann was awarded the Honorary Certificate on 29 September 1918 at the Battle of Bellenglise and Lehaucourt.
However, he was killed by a sniper four days later and never learned that he was awarded the highest British military award.
A memorial stone was unveiled by his two grandchildren at a parade in Rushden, Northamptonshire, on Saturday.
One of his grandsons, Michael Vann, said it was a “great symbolism” that the stone was to be discovered exactly 100 years after his grandfather’s award-winning feat.
According to the London Gazette, Lieutenant-Colonel Vann led his battalion over the Canal de Saint-Quentin on 29 September – “through very thick fog and under heavy fire from field guns and machine guns.”
Later, he crashed towards the firing line and led the line "with great courage" forward before storming a field cannon independently and striking out three of the divisions.
Lieutenant-Colonel Vann was killed by a German sniper on October 4, 1918 – just one month before the war was over.
Michael Vann, 72, said his grandfather’s actions were “something I knew I could never live up to, but something that makes me humble.”
He and his brother Dr. James Vann also laid down a wreath after the parade, which was led by the Brentwood Imperial Corps.
Michael Vann said he “felt very honored to play a role in the parade,” adding: “The bravery of a real hero is demonstrated by the support that comes from many people.”
