Desert Island Discs: Tom Daley felt inferior in terms of sexuality
Olympic diver Tom Daley says he grew up with a sense of inferiority toward everyone because of his sexuality – but it gave him the motivation he needed to succeed.
The 24-year-old says it wasn’t until he was in high school that he realized that “he wasn’t like everyone else.”
In the first program Desert Island Discs on Radio 4 presented by Lauren Laverne, he said he stood up for the gay rights to give others "hope".
He also said that being a parent made him care less about winning the Olympics.
The regular programmer for the traditional program, Kirsty Young, is due to be gone for a few months due to illness.
Daley appeared a little off on Laverne's first broadcast and said he felt "less worthy" than anyone else he grew up with because "it was not socially acceptable to like both boys and girls".
He said: “To this day, these feelings of being inferior and different have been the real motivation and have me the strength and the strength to succeed.”
He wanted to prove that he “was something,” he said, so he did not disappoint everyone when they finally found out about his sexuality.
He is a two-time bronze medalist at the Olympics and has become a highly-profile LGBT ambassador. He used his participation at this year’s Commonwealth Games in Australia to appeal for more countries to decriminalize homosexuality.
He said he stands out because he feels he is lucky to be able to live openly without negative consequences and want to give others “hope.”
The three-time world champion said that the fact that he fell in love with a man - filmmaker Dustin Lance Black from the United States, whom he met in 2013 - "surprised me".
Daley married the Oscar winner, who is 20 years older than him, last year, but he said the age difference had never been a problem.
“When you go through so much at such a young age” – he attended his first Olympics when he was 14, and his father died of cancer three years later – he said it was hard to find someone of the same age who had experienced similar ups and downs.
The couple became parents in June, to a son named Robert Ray Black-Daley, and Daley said his "whole perspective" had been changed.
“If you had asked me last year, it was all about winning a gold medal,” he said.
“You know, there are bigger things than gold medals at the Olympics.
My Olympic gold medalist is Robbie".
The son has the same name as his father Robert, who died in 2011 at the age of 40 after being diagnosed with brain cancer.
Daley said his father did not accept him to die, and one of the last things he asked was if they had gotten tickets to London 2012 – since he wanted to sit on the front row.
“I couldn’t tell him he wouldn’t live long enough to sit on the front row,” he said.
“I held his hands when he stopped breathing, and it wasn’t until he actually stopped breathing and was dead that I finally realized he wasn’t invincible,” he said.
The following year, Daley competed in the 2012 Olympics and won bronze.
“I only knew that this was what I had dreamed of all my life – diving in front of a home crowd at the Olympics, the best feeling ever,” he said.
It also inspired his first song selection – Proud of Heather Small – which meant a lot to him in the run before the Olympics and which still gives him goose bumps.
Desert Island Discs will be broadcast on BBC Radio 4 Sundays at 11:15 BST.
