Germany's new warship delayed once again
German Navy's latest frigate was reportedly completed in 2014 to replace old warships from the Cold War days, but it will not happen until early next year due to failing systems and galloping costs, local media reported.
The completion of the Rheinland-Pfalz, the flagship of the brand-new Baden-Wuerttemberg-class frigates, has now been postponed to the first half of 2019, according to the newspaper Die Zeit citing a military spokesman.
The ship was supposed to have been handed over to the Navy in 2014, but the major problems after delivery followed the ambitious project.
The four ships of the Baden-Wuerttemberg-class navy ordered back in 2007, will replace the old Bremen-class frigates.
It is agreed that they will be equipped with a powerful cannon, a series of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles as well as some stealth technology, such as reduced radar, infrared and acoustic signatures.
Other important features include longer maintenance periods – it should be possible to use the latest frigates for up to two years away from the home port.
However, steady delays mean that the advanced warships – they were said to give Germany strength at sea – will already be out of date before they are put into service, reports Die Zeit.
The fateful F125 frigate created headlines last year, when the German Navy officially refused to put the vessel into operation and returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
This is the first time the Navy has returned a ship to a shipbuilder after delivery.
Little was known about the causes of the return, but German media cited a number of important "software and hardware defects" that rendered the warship useless in a combat mission.
Software defects were particularly important as vessels in the Baden-Wuertemberg class are to be operated by a crew of around 120 sailors - only half of the crew on older Bremen-class frigates.
It was also discovered that the ship has a huge excess weight, which reduces performance and limits the Navy’s ability to make upgrades in the future.
The 7,000-ton "Rheinland-Pfalz" is estimated to be twice as heavy as similar ships of the same class that were used by the Germans during World War II.
In addition to defective hardware, the price tag for the entire project – including the training of the crew – has also started to become a problem.
It is claimed to have reached a staggering <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>3.1 billion – from the original <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>2.2 billion.
The problems surrounding the new frigates are particularly important in light of fresh warnings that Germany’s naval forces are shrinking.
Earlier this year, Hans-Peter Bartels, the head of the German government’s defense committee, confirmed that the navy actually “goes empty for usable ships”.
The official said the problem has escalated over time because old ships were out of service, but no new ships came.
He regrets that none of the frigates of the Baden-Wuerttemberg class could be used by the Navy.
The National Trust steals the secret life of bats
New research carried out at a land estate in the Scottish Highlands will reveal how bats use the landscape in the pursuit of food.
There is hope that the findings will shed new light on the behavior of the unique flying mammals and help design future conservation measures.
The study of researchers at the National Trust for Scotland will follow common bats and dwarf bats as well as brown-throated bats and water bats at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed at key locations around the property to track bat activity throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys using handheld detectors.
Expert audio analyses of all recordings will determine the frequency of the bats and which species do what.
Then a habitat map and a report will be prepared to create a detailed landscape picture of your behavior.
Rob Dewar, nature conservation adviser for NTS, hopes the results will reveal which areas of habitat are most important for bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will be included in the decision on what measures should be taken, such as laying grazing land and how best to take care of the forest for bats and other associated species.
The bat population in Scotland and the United Kingdom has declined considerably over the last century.
They are threatened by construction and construction that affects nesting sites and habitat restriction.
Windmills and lighting can also pose a risk, the same with fly paper and certain chemically treated building materials as well as attacks from house taxes.
The bats are not blind.
But because of their nocturnal hunting habits, they need more ears than eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use advanced ecolocalization to find insects and obstacles on the road when they fly.
NTS, which is responsible for the maintenance of over 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land around the country, takes bats very seriously.
They have ten skilled experts who regularly carry out surveys, surveying of nesting sites and sometimes rescue work.
The organisation has also established Scotland's first and only own bat reserve at the Threave land estate in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland's ten bats.
Property manager David Thompson says the property is the ideal territory for them.
“Here at Threadave we have a perfect area for bats,” he says.
“We have the old buildings, a lot of old trees and the ideal habitat.
But there’s still a lot we don’t know about bats, so the work we do here and at other properties will help us understand more about what they need to thrive.”
He emphasizes how important it is to map the bats before it is carried out maintenance on a property since the inadvertent destruction of a single nesting site can kill up to 400 females and young, and perhaps alienate an entire local population.
Flags are protected, and it is illegal to kill them, harass or disrupt them or destroy their breeding grounds.
Elisabeth Ferrell, a Scottish employee of the Bat Conservation Trust, has urged the public to help in the work.
She says: “We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and for many of the species we simply don’t know how the populations manage.”
