“We need a deal,” Clark said.
The Japanese carmaker said the consequences of delayed border crossings in a possible no-deal Brexit could mean fewer jobs.
The Burnaston plant – which produces Toyota’s Auris and Avensis – produced nearly 150,000 cars last year, 90% of which were exported to the rest of the EU.
“If the UK leaves the EU at the end of March, in my view, we will see production at our factory halt,” said Marvin Cooke, Toyota’s CEO at Burnaston.
Other UK manufacturers have raised concerns about leaving the EU without a deal on how trade across borders will work, including Honda, BMW and Jaguar Land Rover.
BMW, for example, says it will close the Mini factory at Oxford for a month after Brexit.
The main concern is whether what car manufacturers say is supply chain risks in the event of a possible no-deal Brexit.
Toyota's production line is operated on the basis of "order as needed" and parts arrive every 37 minutes from suppliers both in the UK and the EU for cars made on order.
If the UK leaves the EU without a deal on March 29, there could be a stay at the border, which the industry says could lead to delays and a lack of parts.
It will be impossible for Toyota to store more than one day of stock at the Derbyshire plant, the company said, and thus production will cease.
Clark said Theresa May’s Brexit plan for further ties with the EU is “precisely designed to avoid such checks at the border.”
“We need to have a deal, we want to get the best deal that makes us, as I say, not only able to enjoy success at the moment, but that we seize this opportunity,” he said on BBC Radio 4’s Today.
“The message, not only from Toyota but also from other car manufacturers, is that we absolutely need to be able to continue what has been a very successful set of supply chains.”
Toyota could not say how long production would be halted, but warned that increased costs in the long run would reduce the factory's competitiveness and eventually lead to job losses.
Peter Tsouvallaris, who has worked in Burnaston for 24 years and is the union leader at the factory, said that members are becoming increasingly concerned: “My experience dictates that when these jobs disappear, they will never come back.”
