Syria 'ready' for return of refugees, Foreign Minister says
Syria says it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and calls for help to restore the country, which has been razed after more than 7 years of war.
Speaking at the UN National Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem said the country’s conditions are improving.
“Today, the situation on the ground is more stable and secure thanks to the progress in combating terrorism,” he said.
The state continues to rebuild the areas that have been destroyed by terrorists to restore normality.
All conditions are now conducive to the voluntary return of refugees to the country they had to leave due to terrorism and the unilateral economic measures that affected their daily lives and livelihoods.
The UN estimates that more than 5.5 million Syrians have fled the country since the war began in 2011.
In addition, there are six million people still living in the country, who need humanitarian assistance.
Al-Moualem said the Syrian regime would welcome aid to rebuild the devastated country.
But he stressed that conditional assistance or assistance from countries that supported the uprising would not be accepted.
