Update on algae blooming: Concentrations are reduced in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report from the Florida Commission for Fisheries and Wildlife (FWC) shows a general decline in red algae concentrations for parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, there are reports of spot blooms in areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier County – suggesting reduced concentrations.
An inflorescence of red valleys stretches about 210 km along the coast, from the north of Pinellas to the south of Lee County.
Spots are discovered around 16 km off the coast of Hillsborough County, but fewer places than last week.
Red algae have also been observed in Pasco County.
There have been reports of moderately high concentrations at or off the coast of Pinellas County in the last week, low to high concentrations off the coast of Hillsborough County, natural to high concentrations in Manatee County, natural to high concentrations at or off the coast of Sarasota County, natural to medium concentrations in Charlotte County, natural to high concentrations in the high, low to low, low, low, and low, low to high concentrations in Manatee County.
Irritation is still reported in the airways of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier County.
No airway irritation has been reported in northwest Florida over the past week.
